/18/the-tunnel-through-time-gillian-tindall-review-a-new-route-for-an-old-london-journey-crossrail","fields":{"headline":"The Tunnel Through Time: A New Route for an Old London Journey – review","standfirst":"Gillian Tindall’s dizzying history of London’s transport tunnels works best when it reaches Crossrail and the present day","trailText":"Gillian Tindall’s dizzying history of London’s transport tunnels works best when it reaches Crossrail and the present day","byline":"Craig Taylor","body":"<p>Has there ever been a book subject like Crossrail? So unexpectedly dramatic! Loved at conception, despised by some, complex, overstretched, noticeable, public, and at the same time deeply, deeply underground. Although the name first appeared in a study published in 1974, Crossrail was given royal assent in 2008, and the real action began when work commenced in May 2009. If you’re a Londoner, you’ve seen the hoardings, you’ve heard the clanking, and now: time for the book. Gillian Tindall’s attempt to find drama in the great infrastructure project of our time cannot rely on splintering disasters, like the collapse on the Metropolitan works in June 1862. But neither is this simply a story of tunnelling in the dirt. Tindall is interested in excavation into both the layered soil of the city and London’s past.</p> <p>Crossrail has already changed the face of London. That fun little wart called the Astoria was excised in 2009 – “the first indication that Crossrail was for real”, according to one professor of planning. While she gazes at the muddy pit of Crossrail work at Tottenham Court Road, Tindall spies workers moving cautiously, like “well-drilled demons in suits the colour of fire”, as they tear away layers to reveal, once again, just how much of the city is built on what Tindall calls the “vestigial human matter” that can be found throughout. (Enjoy your dinner at Morito tonight; you too, my fellow Londoner, will be vestigial human matter some day.)</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>The book is at its best when Tindall is concerned with the city’s guts, the findings, the workings</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>It’s all exciting and mysterious, but don’t expect a romp. Tindall has read the headlines that accompany construction discoveries. The <em>Evening Standard</em> told readers in May 2009 that “remains linked to workhouse are tested for anthrax and plague”. So she’s ready, like a Mary Whitehouse of public works, to censor anything that resembles “history porn”. It’s not like that. London’s history is not out to kill us. Tindall is keen to tramp down fears that we might be struck dead by the remnants of plague pits, “as if the untamed and noxious spirits of the long past might come back to wreak vengeance on the careless, living, privileged people of today”. If anything, recent discoveries have proven Londoners’ fondness for order. In 2013, Crossrail archaeologists found plague bodies that weren’t chucked in a pit but rather “laid down individually, in neat rows, aligned south-west to north-east”.</p> <p>Londoners don’t change. Tindall delineates the line that connects the self-serving behaviour of Londoners in any era. During Crossrail construction, property owners 30 metres atop underground tunnels were assured their homes wouldn’t suffer subsidence. “The same assurances had had to be given out 100 years before when the first deep tubes were built.” Disapproval of urban growth resurfaces in every era – the ineradicable Nimby gene. Delay has always been a part of London life, although now we can wait on platforms without ingesting the “black fumes that poisoned the palate with sulphur” as George Gissing did in the 1890s.</p> <p>Tindall structures her book so that the Crossrail journey winds east, from Farringdon to Liverpool St to Whitechapel and beyond, and at each stop she jumps around chronologically to tell potted histories and elaborate on what social and architectural history lies in the Crossrail path, from Bedlam to <em>Bleak House</em>. But is this the best way to present popular history? Sometimes Tindall discovers a poetic way to present her time-travelling leaps. In St Giles, for instance, she invites us to imagine as “the film rewinds rapidly backwards: crowded, soot-imbued tenements shake themselves out into old, timbered buildings with vegetable plantations and orchards between, or diminish into thatch-roofed cottages”. It’s a beautiful image. But often the constant chronological to and fro is dizzying as she leaps centuries ahead and back.</p> <p>The book is at its best when Tindall is concerned with the city’s guts, the findings, the workings, when she lets herself witness this great transformation of our own time. Transport aficionados will appreciate her attention to detail while general readers will be heartened to be introduced to this mysterious world. Stick around to the end for the cameo of four hardworking yet modest characters who appear in the book’s final pages. Phyllis, Ada, Victoria and Elizabeth are the real stars – the 1,000-tonne tunnel-boring machines that have offered to us, selflessly, “four and a half million tonnes of deep-down London soil”.</p> <p><em>Craig Taylor’s book </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/londoners.html\" title=\"\"><em>Londoners</em></a><em> is published by Granta. The Tunnel Through Time is published by Chatto &amp; Windus (£20). </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/tunnel-through-time.html?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\"><em>Click here to buy it for £16</em></a><em> </em></p>","wordcount":"764","commentCloseDate":"2016-10-09T06:45:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/52yam","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/8564c756be9c7e4523f1b0427f3eff40f0e67282/0_208_5184_3110/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/history","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","w